### Reading Files in Java

Java provides multiple ways to read files.

---

### Using BufferedReader

```java
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("file.txt"));
String line;
while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
    System.out.println(line);
}
br.close();
```

---

### Using Scanner

```java
Scanner sc = new Scanner(new File("file.txt"));
while (sc.hasNextLine()) {
    System.out.println(sc.nextLine());
}
sc.close();
```

---

### Using Files (Java NIO)

```java
// Read all lines at once
List<String> lines = Files.readAllLines(Paths.get("file.txt"));

// Read entire file as string
String content = Files.readString(Paths.get("file.txt"));

// Read as stream
Files.lines(Paths.get("file.txt")).forEach(System.out::println);
```

---

### Reading Binary Files

```java
// Using FileInputStream
FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("file.dat");
int b;
while ((b = fis.read()) != -1) {
    // process byte
}

// Using Files.readAllBytes
byte[] allBytes = Files.readAllBytes(Paths.get("file.dat"));
```

---

### Reading Methods Comparison

| Method | Best For | Memory |
|--------|----------|--------|
| BufferedReader | Large text files | Line by line |
| Scanner | Parsing tokens | Flexible |
| Files.readAllLines | Small files | Entire file |
| Files.readString | Small text files | Entire file |

> **Key Point:** For large files, use BufferedReader or Files.lines() to avoid memory issues. Use try-with-resources for automatic resource management.

codeExample:
import java.io.*;
import java.nio.file.*;
import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        // Create a sample file
        Files.writeString(Paths.get("sample.txt"), 
            "Line 1: Hello\nLine 2: World\nLine 3: Java");

        // Method 1: BufferedReader
        System.out.println("=== BufferedReader ===");
        try (BufferedReader br = Files.newBufferedReader(Paths.get("sample.txt"))) {
            String line;
            while ((line = br.readLine()) != null) {
                System.out.println(line);
            }
        }

        // Method 2: Files.readAllLines
        System.out.println("\n=== Files.readAllLines ===");
        List<String> lines = Files.readAllLines(Paths.get("sample.txt"));
        for (String line : lines) {
            System.out.println(line);
        }

        // Method 3: Files.readString (Java 11+)
        System.out.println("\n=== Files.readString ===");
        String content = Files.readString(Paths.get("sample.txt"));
        System.out.println(content);
    }
}
